n":{"city":"Troy","state":"New York","country":"United States"},"primary_url":"https://en.wikipedia.org/wiki/Emma_Willard_School","primary_url_label":"Wikipedia","primary_persons":["H00597"],"hooker_connected_people":["H00597","H00598","HD2963","HD2964","HD3148"],"person_ids":["X02107"],"related_institutions":[],"related_landmarks":[],"tags":[],"sources":[],"notes":"Founded 1814 by Emma Hart Willard (H00597) in Middlebury, VT as the Middlebury Female Seminary — the first women's higher education institution in the United States. Moved to Troy, NY in 1821 and renamed Troy Female Seminary. Renamed Emma Willard School in 1895. Willard resigned leadership in 1838 to her son John Willard (H01550). Almira Hart Phelps (H00598) was vice-principal; wrote Lectures on Botany (1829) during this tenure — 10,000 copies sold in three years. Twelve or more Berlin CT girls attended on Willard's invitation and expense, including Jane Porter Hart (HD2963) and Harriet Hart (HD2964). As of 2026: endowment $119M; grades 9-12 plus postgraduate; #1 private school Upstate NY 2018.\n[former/alt detail] Formerly: Middlebury Female Seminary (1814); Troy Female Seminary (1821). Now: Emma Willard School."}},"crossConnections":[{"type":"mentor_student","related_id":"H00597","link_text":"Emma Hart Willard","display_label":"Emma Hart Willard invited her to Troy Seminary; she went on to teach in Kensington schools.","slug":"emma-willard-1787"}]}